<TITLE> UK's Prince William to fulfil flying dream </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Oct 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's Prince William is to follow in his father's footsteps by learning to fly with the Royal Air Force next year, his spokesman said on Wednesday. William, 25, second-in-line to the throne, will spend four months with the RAF from next January, piloting helicopters and fixed-wing planes. His father Prince Charles, grandfather Prince Philip and uncle Prince Andrew all qualified as pilots with the RAF. William, who completed an army officer training course last year, will then go on to spend time in the Royal Navy next summer, training on warships and submarines. "His time with the RAF will ... allow him to realise a lifetime ambition to learn to fly," a royal spokesman said. "He will be able to share the working lives of airmen and sailors." In 2006, William left the prestigious Royal Military Academy Sandhurst, an officer training centre west of London that takes recruits from around the world. His first posting as an officer was with the Blue and Royals, one of the two senior regiments that form the Household Cavalry, which guards his grandmother, Queen Elizabeth. With the rank of second lieutenant, William commands a troop of four armoured reconnaissance vehicles, crewed by 12 men. Global media interest in the young prince has spiralled in recent months, driven mainly by his on-off relationship Kate Middleton, whom he met at university in Scotland. William complained last week that paparazzi photographers chased them in cars and on motorbikes when they left a London nightclub just days after an inquest opened into his mother's death in a Paris car crash. Princess Diana died in 1997 after the car she was travelling in hit a pillar in a Paris tunnel while being pursued by photographers. Her companion, Dodi al-Fayed and the driver, Henri Paul were also killed in the collision. Investigations by French and British police conclude the deaths were an accident caused by an inebriated Paul driving too fa
